text.tspan: When a set of objects is small, it is easy to list the objects and count them one by one. When the set is too large to count that way,

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 12px; line-height: normal; font-family: Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: and when the objects are related in a patterned or systematic way

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 40px; line-height: normal; font-family: Verdana; cursor: pointer;

-webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 12px; line-height: normal; font-family: Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: The term set has been used informally in this review to mean a collection of objects that have some property, whether it is the

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 12px; line-height: normal; font-family: Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: collection of all positive integers, all points in a circular region,

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 12px; line-height: normal; font-family: Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: The objects of a set are called members or elements. Some sets are finite, which means that their members can be completely counted.

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 12px; line-height: normal; font-family: Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: Finite sets can, in principle, have all of their members listed, using curly brackets, such as the set of odd digits { 1 ,3 ,7 ,9}

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 16px; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Courier new'; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: Sets that are not finite are called infinite sets, such as the set of all integers.

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 16px; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Courier new'; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: A set that has no members is called the empty set and is denoted by the symbol

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 16px; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Courier new'; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: A set with one or more members is called nonempty.
